rsaries to keep secret the interventions they detect, as when American leaders concealed clashes with Soviet pilots during the Korean War. Escalation concerns can also cause leaders to ignore covert interventions that have become an open secret. From Nazi Germany's role in the Spanish Civil War to American covert operations during the Vietnam War, Carson presents new insights about some of the most influential conflicts of the twentieth century.Parting the curtain on the secret side of modern war, Secret Wars provides important lessons about how rival state powers collude and compete, and the ways in which they avoid outright military confrontations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aUnited States-Foreign relations. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh  aAfghanistan.  aAmerican intelligence.  aAmerican weapons.  aCold War.  aCondor Legion.  aGerman intervention.  aGreat War.  aIranian covert intervention.  aIraq occupation.  aKorean War.  aLyndon Johnson.  aNon-Intervention Committee.  aRichard Nixon.  aSoviet cross-border.  aSpain.  aSpanish Civil War.  aStinger missile system.  aU.S. aid program.  aU.S. military activity.  aVietnam War.  aWorld War I.  aair supremacy.  aair-to-air combat.  aairpower.  acivil wars.  acollusion.  aconflict escalation.  aconflicts.  acounterinsurgency.  acovert intervention.  acovert military intervention.  acovert operations.  acovertness.  acyberconflict.  acyberwarfare.  adirect combat.  adirect communication.  adomestic opposition.  adrones.  aescalation control.  aescalation dangers.  aescalation dynamics.  aescalation potential.  aescalation process.  aforeign combat participation.  aforeign wars.  agovernment secrets.  agovernments.  alarge-scale conflict.